Absolutely.

But there’s a funny thing about luck.

The more patterns you notice, the more “luck” starts showing up.

A fisherman who notices birds, current seams, water color, tide, season, and structure seems lucky.

A quarterback who notices defensive alignment before the snap seems lucky.

A business owner who catches a trend six months early seems lucky.

From the outside, it often looks like luck because observers only see the outcome, not the thousands of tiny observations that preceded it.

At the same time, genuine luck exists too.

You can do everything right and a pelican just happens to fly across your field of view at the perfect moment.

You can make a random phone call that changes your life.

You can meet your future spouse because you were standing in the wrong line.

The interesting part is that life seems to reward both:

* Preparedness — noticing what’s there.
* Openness — allowing something unexpected to arrive.

Too much preparedness and you miss surprises.
Too much openness and you drift without direction.

The sweet spot is often:

Pay attention. Then leave room for luck.

Or in your language:

Read the water. Then cast anyway.

Because sometimes the fish are exactly where the signs say they’ll be.

And sometimes there’s a fish where no fish has any business being. 😉